0":"1600","1499":"1499","1520":"1520","1564":"1564","1573":"1573","1528":"1528","1527":"1527","Netherlands":"Nederlandene","Poortugaal, Albrandswaard, Zuid-Holland, Netherlands":"Poortugaal, Zuid-Holland, Nederlandene"},"nl":{"1520–":"1520–Overleden","1520–Male":"1520–Overleden","1528–1600":"1528–1600","–Female":"Overleden","1536–1624":"1536–1624","1490–1579":"1490–1579","1499–1564":"1499–1564","1572":"1572","1581":"1581","1490":"1490","1536":"1536","1624":"1624","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1499":"1499","1520":"1520","1564":"1564","1573":"1573","1528":"1528","1527":"1527","Netherlands":"Nederland","Poortugaal, Albrandswaard, Zuid-Holland, Netherlands":"Poortugaal, Zuid-Holland, Nederland"},"en":{"1520–":"1520–Deceased","1520–Male":"1520–Deceased","1528–1600":"1528–1600","–Female":"Deceased","1536–1624":"1536–1624","1490–1579":"1490–1579","1499–1564":"1499–1564","1572":"1572","1581":"1581","1490":"1490","1536":"1536","1624":"1624","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1499":"1499","1520":"1520","1564":"1564","1573":"1573","1528":"1528","1527":"1527","Netherlands":"Netherlands","Poortugaal, Albrandswaard, Zuid-Holland, Netherlands":"Poortugaal, South Holland, Netherlands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"van","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"Essen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: habitational name from any of several places called Essen, for example in the Ruhr.","English: variant of   Esson   (see   Easton  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Esson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans.","Scottish (Aberdeenshire): from a shortened and altered form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Adamh</i> (see   Adam  ). This surname was sometimes confused with 2 below.","English and Scottish: variant of   Easton  , although in some instances the Scottish surname may reflect the reverse process, in which the name in 1 above has acquired an intrusive <i>-t-</i>."]},{"name":"Essman","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Essmann</b>: habitational name, a variant of   Essen  , with the suffix <i>man</i> ‘man’ or nickname for a big eater, from the agent derivative of Middle High German <i>ezzen</i> ‘to eat’."]}]},{"name":"Rutger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Rüdiger ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rüdiger","meanings":["from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This is the name of a hero in the <i>Nibelungenlied</i>.  See  Roger   ."]}]},{"name":"Willemsen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch and North German: patronymic from the personal name   Willem  , a variant of   Wilhelm  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Willem","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1356698,"age":52,"year":"1572","julianDay":2295221,"description":"William of Orange was recognized as viceroy of Holland, Friesland and Utrecht.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1356699,"age":53,"year":"1573","julianDay":2295587,"description":"The siege of Leiden between the rebels and the Spanish. 1574 The dikes were opened allowing a Dutch fleet to sail over the flood waters and rescue Leiden.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1356701,"age":61,"year":"1581","julianDay":2298509,"description":"The Dutch declared their independence from Spain.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1356702,"age":61,"year":"1581","julianDay":2298509,"description":"The United Provinces declare their independence from Spain.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1356710,"age":104,"year":"1624","julianDay":2314214,"description":"The Dutch conquered Salvador, Brazil.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Rutger Willemsen van Essen was born in 1520, in Netherlands, his father, Hendrik van Essen, was 30 and his mother, Barbara van de Padevoirt, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Maijken Philipsen. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1520–":"1520–Surnud","1520–Male":"1520–Surnud","1528–1600":"1528–1600","–Female":"Surnud","1536–1624":"1536–1624","1490–1579":"1490–1579","1499–1564":"1499–1564","1572":"1572","1581":"1581","1490":"1490","1536":"1536","1624":"1624","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1499":"1499","1520":"1520","1564":"1564","1573":"1573","1528":"1528","1527":"1527","Netherlands":"Madalmaad","Poortugaal, Albrandswaard, Zuid-Holland, Netherlands":"Poortugaal, Zuid-Holland, Madalmaad"},"fi":{"1520–":"1520–Kuollut","1520–Male":"1520–Kuollut","1528–1600":"1528–1600","–Female":"Kuollut","1536–1624":"1536–1624","1490–1579":"1490–1579","1499–1564":"1499–1564","1572":"1572","1581":"1581","1490":"1490","1536":"1536","1624":"1624","1579"